  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is a good amount of money yearly to live more than comfortably in the USA?",
  "response": "The amount of money needed to live \"more than comfortably\" in the USA varies widely depending on location, lifestyle, family size, and personal preferences. However, here are some general guidelines:\n\n### **1. For a Single Person**\n- **Low Cost of Living Areas (e.g., Midwest, rural areas):** $60,000\u2013$80,000 per year.\n- **Medium Cost of Living Areas (e.g., suburbs in Texas or Florida):** $80,000\u2013$100,000 per year.\n- **High Cost of Living Areas (e.g., New York City, San Francisco):** $120,000\u2013$150,000+ per year.\n\n### **2. For a Family of Four (2 Adults + 2 Kids)**\n- **Low Cost of Living Areas:** $100,000\u2013$120,000 per year.\n- **Medium Cost of Living Areas:** $120,000\u2013$150,000 per year.\n- **High Cost of Living Areas:** $200,000\u2013$300,000+ per year.\n\n### **What \"More Than Comfortable\" Entails**\n- Living in a nice home or apartment in a safe, desirable area.\n- Owning reliable vehicles (if needed).\n- Ability to save and invest for the future.\n- Travel and leisure activities.\n- Dining out and entertainment without financial stress.\n- Covering healthcare, education, and childcare costs comfortably.\n\n### **Factors That Influence Costs**\n- **Housing:** The biggest expense. In high-cost cities like NYC or SF, housing alone can eat up a significant portion of income.\n- **Healthcare:** Insurance premiums, deductibles, and out-of-pocket costs vary.\n- **Transportation:** Owning a car vs. relying on public transit.\n- **Lifestyle:** How often you dine out, travel, or indulge in hobbies.\n- **Taxes:** State and local taxes can vary significantly.\n\n### **Conclusion**\nTo live \"more than comfortably\" in the USA, aim for **$100,000\u2013$150,000+ per year** for a single person and **$150,000\u2013$300,000+ per year** for a family, depending on your location and lifestyle. In high-cost areas, you may need significantly more to maintain a luxurious standard of living.",
